It works.
But the method queryKeys should not add the prefix twice (method parameter and getPrefixedIdentifier). The result of queryKeys cannot be used with get or delete becaus of the prefix.
This could be solved like this:

``` php
protected function getPrefixedIdentifier($id)
    {
        $options = $this->getOptions();

        if ((!empty($options['prefix'])) && (strpos($id, $options['prefix']) === false)) {
            return $options['prefix'] . $id;
        }

        return $id;
    }
```

and 

``` php
public function queryKeys($prefix = null)
    {
        $options = $this->getOptions();
        if ($prefix === null) {
            return $options['redis']->getKeys($this->getPrefixedIdentifier('*'));
        } else {
            return $options['redis']->getKeys($prefix . '*');
        }
    }
```

the result of getQueryKeys looks good, but you shoul change line 147 to:

``` php
$result = $options['redis']->getKeys($prefix . '*');
```

For example:

``` php
$cache = new \Phalcon\Cache\Backend\Redis($frontend, array(
  'redis'  => $redis,
  'prefix' => 'testPrefix',
));
$cache->save('key1', 'value');
foreach ($cache->queryKeys('testPrefix') as $key) {
  echo $cache->get($key);
}
```

The foreach has null entries...

The argument of method «queryKeys» named «$prefix» is not the same as object property $option['prefix'].
$option['prefix'] is internal data.
This is just a little misunderstood in variables naming.
You've provided a correct link.
When i setup cache backend I may know nothing about the value of prefix in options, the library must do all dirty work for me.
